'''Heroic bloodshed''' is a genre of [[Hong Kong action cinema]] revolving around stylized action sequences and dramatic themes such as brotherhood, duty, honour, redemption and [[violence]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Hong Kong's Heroic Bloodshed |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XpAIAAAACAAJ|last=Fitzgerald|first=Martin|year=2000 |publisher=Pocket Essentials |isbn=1-903047-07-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=A-Z of Cult Films and Film-Makers |last=Davies |first=Steven Paul |authorlink= |year=2001 |publisher=Batsford |location= |isbn=0-7134-8704-6 |pages=26 }}</ref> The term ''heroic bloodshed'' was coined by editor Rick Baker in the magazine ''Eastern Heroes''<ref>{{cite book |title=Hong Kong Action Cinema |last=Logan |first=Bey |authorlink= |year=1996 |publisher=Overlook Press |location= |isbn=0-87951-663-1 |pages=191 }}</ref> in the late 1980s, specifically referring to the styles of directors [[John Woo]] and [[Ringo Lam]]. Baker defined the genre as "a Hong Kong action film that features a lot of [[Gun fu|gun play]] and [[Gangster film|gangsters]] rather than [[kung fu]]. Lots of blood. Lots of action."<ref>{{cite book |title=City on Fire: Hong Kong Cinema |last=Stokes |first=Lisa Odham |authorlink= |author2=Michael Hoover |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3AGX0YSmaYYC&pg=PA333|year=1999 |publisher=Verso |location= |isbn=1-85984-716-1 |pages=333 }}</ref> Woo's breakthrough film ''[[A Better Tomorrow]]'' (1986) largely set the template for the genre.<ref>{{cite book |last=Morton |first=Lisa |authorlink= |editor= |others= |title=The Cinema of Tsui Hark |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hv3yJ6MaoYsC&pg=PA62 |accessdate= |edition= |series= |year=2001 |publisher=McFarland |location= |isbn=0-7864-0990-8}}</ref> Woo has also been a major influence in its continued popularity and evolution in his following works, namely ''[[A Better Tomorrow 2]]'' (1987), ''[[The Killer (1989 film)|The Killer]]'' (1989) and ''[[Hard Boiled]]'' (1992).<ref>{{cite book |last=Morton |first=Lisa |authorlink= |editor= |others= |title=The Cinema of Tsui Hark |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hv3yJ6MaoYsC&pg=PA62 |accessdate= |edition= |series= |year=2001 |publisher=McFarland |location= |isbn=0-7864-0990-8 |oclc= |doi= |pages=62 |chapter= |chapterurl= }} </ref>
The heroic bloodshed genre had a considerable impact on [[world cinema]], including [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]], in the 1990s.<ref name="Diplomat">{{cite news|last=Volodzko|first=David|title=30 Years Later, This Chinese Film Still Echoes in Hollywood|url=https://thediplomat.com/2015/06/30-years-later-this-chinese-film-still-echoes-in-hollywood/|work=[[The Diplomat]]|date=13 June 2015}}</ref> Woo introduced his brand of heroic bloodshed to Hollywood in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fang|first1=Karen|title=John Woo's A Better Tomorrow: Autobiographical Stories by Modern Chinese Women Writers|date=2004|publisher=[[Hong Kong University Press]]|isbn=9789622096523|page=85|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BogcBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA85|language=en}}</ref> Lam's ''[[City on Fire (1987 film)|City on Fire]]'' (1987) inspired [[Quentin Tarantino]]'s ''[[Reservoir Dogs]]'' (1992);<ref>{{cite book|last1=Spicer|first1=Andrew|title=Historical Dictionary of Film Noir|date=2010|publisher=[[Scarecrow Press]]|isbn=9780810873780|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ixVekSdvQCMC&pg=PA141|language=en}}</ref> Tarantino was an admirer of the heroic bloodshed genre.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Ingham|first1=Michael|title=Johnnie To Kei-Fung's PTU|date=2009|publisher=[[Hong Kong University Press]]|isbn=9789622099197|page=115|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2ROqAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA115|language=en}}</ref> ''The Killer'' also heavily influenced [[Luc Besson]]’s ''[[Léon: The Professional]]'' (1994).<ref name="Diplomat"/>
==Motifs== {{Unreferenced section|date=January 2011}} Protagonists in these films are often good-willed criminals, typically [[Triad (underground society)|Triad]] members, [[Hit man|hit men]], or thieves with a strict code of ethics, which in some cases leads to the betrayal of their employers and the saving of many intended victims. The police officer with a conscience, who cannot be corrupted in any way, is also common, and is usually modeled after the [[Hardboiled|hardboiled detective]]. Loyalty, family and brotherhood are the most typical themes of the genre. Heroic bloodshed films generally have a strong emotional angle, not only between, but during action sequences.
Pistols and [[submachine gun]]s are frequently utilized by the heroes due to the light weight they provide, enabling their wielders to move more quickly. They are frequently [[dual wield]]ed. The heroes are extremely agile and implement rolls, dives, slides, and falls while they duel, making for a graceful, [[ballet]]-like performance in the midst of gunfire.
Heroic bloodshed films often end on a downbeat or tragic note with the main heroes either dead, arrested by the police, or severely incapacitated.
